class Solution {
public:
    int smallestRepunitDivByK(int k) {
        int remainder = 0;
        for (int length = 1; length <= k; ++length) {
            remainder = (remainder * 10 + 1) % k;
            if (remainder == 0) {
                return length;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(k)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates up to k times, maintaining a running remainder when dividing the current number (comprised of 'length' number of 1s) by k. If the remainder becomes 0, it means we've found the smallest n divisible by k. The use of modulo operation prevents n from growing too large.

